  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Pete Crow-Armstrong Walks Off Giants in Ten Innings",
    "subheadline": "Pete Crow-Armstrong's Two-Homer Effort Powers Cubs to 10th-Inning Victory",
    "lead_angle": "Pete Crow-Armstrong’s single to center field in the bottom of the tenth scored the winning run, lifting the Chicago Cubs to a 3-2 walk-off victory over the San Francisco Giants. Ryan Rolison earned the win on the mound for Chicago, pitching a scoreless tenth. Sam Hentges was tagged with the loss for the Giants after surrendering the deciding run.\n\nThe game remained scoreless through five frames before San Francisco’s Rafael Devers broke the deadlock with a solo home run in the sixth inning. The Cubs responded promptly when Pete Crow-Armstrong launched his first solo shot of the afternoon to knot the score at one run apiece. The Giants later pushed ahead for a 2-1 lead, but Crow-Armstrong again answered in the late innings with his second solo blast, drawing Chicago even at two and forcing extra innings at Wrigley Field.\n\nCrow-Armstrong was the key performer, finishing 4-for-5 with both Chicago home runs and two runs batted in, repeatedly keeping the North Siders alive. His offensive heroics delivered a pivotal win for the Cubs, advancing their standing in a tight National League Central Division race.",
    "reason": "Extra-inning walk-off — the purest combination of tension and resolution the sport offers."
